HEADWORD: Sol
<hw>Sol</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The sun.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Alchem.)</fld> <def>Gold; -- so called from its
brilliancy, color, and value.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sol</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sol
<hw>Sol</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It.]</ety>
<fld>(Mus.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A syllable applied in solmization to
the note G, or to the fifth tone of any diatonic scale.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>The tone itself.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sol</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sol
<hw>Sol</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Sou</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A sou.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A silver and gold coin of Peru. The silver
<xex>sol</xex> is the unit of value, and is worth about 68
cents.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

